cess_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aParis remains one of the most fascinating cities in the world. It provides a measure of excellence in many areas of culture, and it is itself constantly being measured, both by its lovers and by its critics. This book presents a series of studies on the images of Paris presented by writers (mostly Canadian, from John Glassco to Mavis Gallant to Lola Lemire Tostevin), but also in such other areas as social history and personal memoir. The result is a wide-ranging discussion of the city's history in 20th century literature and thought, which will appeal to all those who love Paris, or who have ever walked on its streets.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticismx20th century. 0aCanadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aLittérature canadiennexHistoire et critiquex20e siècle. 0aParis (France) dans la littérature. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / General.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aLiterary Nonfiction.  aMemoir.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012z978311127413308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012z978311127716540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978088864783240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780888647832423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780888647832/original  a978-3-11-127413-3  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2012b2012  a978-3-11-127716-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2012b2012  aGBV-deGruyter-alles